As someone with some educational background in data analytics and a certificate in data analytics and data analytical programming, the numbers never lie. However, the stories we translate from them can, because all of that is up to human interpretation. There is always some new statistic, some new metric, or something quantitative and qualitative we can derive to find value. I have not deep dived the analytics of basketball, but this video showcased some causation and correlation on data that ties Jimmy Butler being a team with enhanced performance.

The issue with analytics in sports will always be that some of these values are understated, people interpret things wrong, and there is no set value for every analytic that applies the exact same way to every organization, team, 5-man squad or rotation, player, or even game or possession. Data analytics and science, like analysis based on understanding of basketball, has so much nuisance that it requires constant evaluation.

Organizations that constantly look at data analytics and understanding of fundamentals of basketball and constantly analyze it with the skills, expertise and history in them are paramount, but secretly just as paramount is constantly expanding yourself and looking for constant growth and viewpoints that are different from your own. In the end, it is all truly not unlike anything in learning, business or personal growth.
